  ],
  "activity_sections": [
    {
      "key": "944b875d-9674-441c-815f-8ed23f92b3e9",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "- **This is a pilot, so things change!** Please always refer to the Slide Decks and Speaker Notes for the latest updates.\n- If the rest of this lesson plan is blank, don't worry! It just means we're still in the process of updating this lesson plan on our website and that process can sometimes get delayed! However, **the slides are always up to date** and the speaker notes contain everything you need to run the lesson. ",
        "name": "Pilot Information"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "944b875d-9674-441c-815f-8ed23f92b3e9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f2abce3f-f9ef-4fc9-941a-f7b2b06b5b2b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3aab8e3e-14f5-4c29-86ab-68b63baaeaca",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Get started with our new Self-Paced Professional Learning to explore the curriculum and Music Lab! Feel confident and prepared as you start teaching the unit! [**Click here to start learning!**](https://studio.code.org/s/self-paced-pl-teaching-computer-science-discoveries-music-lab/lessons/1/levels/1)",
        "name": "Professional Learning"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3aab8e3e-14f5-4c29-86ab-68b63baaeaca",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f2abce3f-f9ef-4fc9-941a-f7b2b06b5b2b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4e2b2e6c-dfaf-427a-a17b-7a22194f1e70",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "**Two Warm-Up Options:** This lesson has two warm-up options, depending on whether or not students have been previously introduced to the Problem Solving Process.\n\n**Option 1** is for classrooms that have not been introduced to the Problem Solving Process. The warm up is longer than normal because it introduces the Problem Solving Process through a brief activity and a video.\n\n**Option 2** is for classrooms that have been introduced to the Problem Solving Process in a previous unit. The warm-up is shorter and acts as a quick review of the Problem Solving Process."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4e2b2e6c-dfaf-427a-a17b-7a22194f1e70",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a6ea07ca-b80a-4053-b5d2-c6937f1f9797"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "75283f55-15ed-42ea-9ade-8cad18c49ea8",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "In this unit, we'll take on the role of music experience designers to help clients with their design problem. The word \"problem\" can refer to lots of different situations - I could say I have a problem for homework, a problem with my brother, and a problem with my car, and all three mean very different things.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Problem Solving Word Search",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "75283f55-15ed-42ea-9ade-8cad18c49ea8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a6ea07ca-b80a-4053-b5d2-c6937f1f9797"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "39c53450-fa77-4c5e-b2ae-97d7aff0177b",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Prompt:**  What's an example of a problem you've had to solve recently?"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "39c53450-fa77-4c5e-b2ae-97d7aff0177b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a6ea07ca-b80a-4053-b5d2-c6937f1f9797"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "97c3eb25-6cd9-4446-93e0-34f5838dff78",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Circulate & Distribute:** Have students share their thoughts with a neighbor. Listen for examples that may be worth using as examples throughout the lesson. \n\nAs students share, distribute a copy of the [Word Search](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1M1_eMuqtPX4Yo2eQl3JOo9MbSyPB-4C1mLYyNlh1HKc/view) to each student, face down. Make sure students don't start the word search ahead of time.\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "97c3eb25-6cd9-4446-93e0-34f5838dff78",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a6ea07ca-b80a-4053-b5d2-c6937f1f9797"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2d724957-9957-4201-a16e-dacbdc10dd69",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Since we will most likely be faced with some problems to solve in this unit, today, we are going to learn about and practice an effective strategy for when we need to solve problems. We'll start with a simple problem: solving a word search.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2d724957-9957-4201-a16e-dacbdc10dd69",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a6ea07ca-b80a-4053-b5d2-c6937f1f9797"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "37e82e83-60a0-4717-a844-9a33e4b006f5",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Prompt:** What is the problem you are trying to solve when you do a word search?\n\n**Discuss:** Allow students to discuss their ideas with a classmate before sharing them with the entire class.\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Guide students to the idea that the problem of a word search is that there are hidden words throughout the grid of letters and thus the goal of a word search is to find all the words in the list.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Prompt:** What are the different strategies that someone could use for finding words? What are the pros and cons of each strategy?\n\n**Discuss:** Allow students to silently record their ideas in writing for a minute. Afterward, invite them to share what they wrote with a neighbor and then finally bring the whole class together to develop a classwide list of strategies.\n\n**Discussion Goal:** This is a quick, low-stakes brainstorm that asks students to bring in their own experiences with word searches and identify strategies they may have used or could use. Student responses may vary but may include the following strategies:\n* Scan each row from left to right followed by scanning each column from top to bottom.\n* Check surrounding letters. Once you found the first letter or a key letter in a word you’re searching for, check the letters around it to see if you should keep going. For example, if you have a word with Q in it, if there’s no U next to it, then you need to keep searching.\n* Look for words that have less-common letters in them such as words with a Q, X, J, or Z\n* Look for words with letter pairs, such as double letters or QU\n* Look for more than one word at a time.\n* Turn the puzzle upside down\n\n**Do This:** Direct students to pick ONE strategy from the list that they want to try and put a “#1” next to it in their journals to indicate it was their first strategy used. Once they pick a strategy, direct students to use that strategy in their word search.\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "It is important to let the students know that if at any time the strategy they picked is not working, they should feel free to go back to the list of strategies and pick a different one, making sure to put a number next to the new strategy."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "37e82e83-60a0-4717-a844-9a33e4b006f5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a6ea07ca-b80a-4053-b5d2-c6937f1f9797"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e13470ca-d351-4561-a562-fb370e59b19d",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Circulate:** Give students a few minutes to find as many words as possible. It is okay if they don’t find every word. You may bring everyone back together once everyone has found at least several of the words on the list.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Prompt:** Display and have students reflect on each of the following prompts:\n* Were you successful in solving this word search problem? How do you know?\n* What strategy did you pick and how did it work for you?\n* Did anyone change strategies at any point … why or why not?\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "As you lead this discussion, you may choose to do a quick raise of hand poll to find out who was successful, or on track to be successful if they didn’t get a chance to finish. Additionally, you can also instruct students to pick two of the questions to answer."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e13470ca-d351-4561-a562-fb370e59b19d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a6ea07ca-b80a-4053-b5d2-c6937f1f9797"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "17f82a89-8f20-4ac2-a739-395394e146c1",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Discussion Goal:** This discussion serves as a way to get students to reflect on how they did solving this problem and to give students a moment to recognize if they changed strategies and why or if they would solve a problem like this differently next time."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "17f82a89-8f20-4ac2-a739-395394e146c1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a6ea07ca-b80a-4053-b5d2-c6937f1f9797"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e865dfd5-ab2e-4d4a-a2bb-d180b0ad9094",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show students the [r the_problem_solving_process/csd-programming-with-music-lab-2025-pilot/unversioned] video in the slides.\n\n**Questions to Consider with Video:**\n* What are the 4 steps to the Problem-Solving Process?",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "The Problem Solving Process",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Videos are used throughout the curriculum to spark discussions, supplement key concepts with additional explanations and examples, and expose students to the various roles and backgrounds of individuals in computer science.\n\nWhile interacting with the video, turn on closed captioning so students can also read along as they watch.\n\nTo encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the **[Guide to Curriculum Videos](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1c2hF3CaTJacvwDy4y_9-m1jSkSPmK__F6pDPetXVvy4/view)**."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e865dfd5-ab2e-4d4a-a2bb-d180b0ad9094",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a6ea07ca-b80a-4053-b5d2-c6937f1f9797"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f6c29097-b00a-4683-bccf-cacda0e53825",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Discuss and Display:** Briefly discuss with students what parts of the warm-up activity they felt fell into each step of the problem-solving process before displaying the example answers in the slides:\n* Define: when we put into our own words what the problem of a word search is and what the goal is\n* Prepare: the brainstorming of different strategies that could be used to solve a word search\n* Try: when we picked a strategy and tried to find the words\n* Reflect: when we reflected on how they did at the end",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "This is a good point to remind students that the problem-solving process is a cycle and there should be times when they need to repeat steps. For example, if they went back to the list of strategies and picked a different one at any point when solving this problem, they were not only doing the “Reflect” step without realizing it but going back to the “Prepare” and “Try” steps again.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f6c29097-b00a-4683-bccf-cacda0e53825",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a6ea07ca-b80a-4053-b5d2-c6937f1f9797"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "cd5b1e29-a9a1-4bb4-b635-e3679e5d1f9a",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Now that we're familiar with the problem-solving process, let's explore how we can use it when designing music for clients. ",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "cd5b1e29-a9a1-4bb4-b635-e3679e5d1f9a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a6ea07ca-b80a-4053-b5d2-c6937f1f9797"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9e8bad2e-2655-4013-aff6-a786c3fa8024",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "**Two Warm-Up Options:** This lesson has two warm-up options, depending on whether or not students have been previously introduced to the Problem-Solving Process.\n\nOption 2 is for classrooms that have been introduced to the Problem-Solving Process in a previous unit. The warm-up is shorter and acts as a quick review of the Problem-Solving Process"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9e8bad2e-2655-4013-aff6-a786c3fa8024",
        "lesson_activity.key": "890c9beb-6545-4710-8ea2-b2095353e7a0"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "bd2daf00-3d15-4479-b20b-915928b38a98",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "In this unit, we'll take on the role of music experience designers to help clients with their design problem. Today, we are going to remind ourselves about the Problem Solving Process and eventually we will apply it to the music we create.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Revisit The Problem Solving Process",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "bd2daf00-3d15-4479-b20b-915928b38a98",
        "lesson_activity.key": "890c9beb-6545-4710-8ea2-b2095353e7a0"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5fb87c4a-13da-4a7e-b07d-1e9af3ac4130",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Prompt:** What do you remember about the Problem-Solving Process?\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Based on student responses, the teacher should lead students through a discussion about the four steps of the Problem-Solving Process and what they remember to be involved in each step.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Prompt:** Based on what you know about the Problem-Solving Process, what do you think each step could look like when designing an song?\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Even though students haven't designed music yet, guide students to imagine the steps involved from having the first inspiration for a song to having it created. Some ideas may include:\n* Define: Deciding what you want the mood of the song to be or who you want to make it for\n* Prepare: Listening to other songs and deciding what kinds of sounds, effects, and patterns you want to use or thinking about how the user might interact with the music.\n* Try: Creating a basic version of the song (even if it doesn’t have all of the features)\n* Reflect: Showing it to friends to get feedback and improving the song\n\nAs students finish discussing, transition to the main activity.\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5fb87c4a-13da-4a7e-b07d-1e9af3ac4130",
        "lesson_activity.key": "890c9beb-6545-4710-8ea2-b2095353e7a0"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1c3f5815-4a9d-4913-91b8-28e96409c004",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "In this unit, we’re going to learn how to create interactive songs using Music Lab, which starts with thinking about who we’re creating music for. Sometimes we make music based on our own interests or moods, but it’s also important to think about designing songs that other people will enjoy or connect with.\n\nEventually, we’ll apply the problem-solving process to help us actually code our musical ideas. But today, we’re going to focus on how to use the problem-solving process to design songs and musical experiences that meet the needs of both ourselves and others.",
        "name": "Recommending Song Ideas to Clients",
        "progression_name": "User Stories"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1c3f5815-4a9d-4913-91b8-28e96409c004",
        "lesson_activity.key": "911a527c-f6c9-45c4-8483-033415340b87"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4f9218ff-1d7c-4408-a619-e5f4085590ab",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Group:** Put students in pairs.\n\n**Distribute:** Pass out a copy of the [activity guide](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1YDGmbxZSHZhvMWVPzoawNm0ceKRoPffgt1kc0HQDWhk/view) to each student. ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "**Answer Keys & Exemplars:** An answer key or exemplar is provided for verified teachers as part of the resources in this lesson plan. If you do not see an answer key or exemplar listed as a resource, [follow these steps](https://support.code.org/hc/en-us/articles/115001550131-Becoming-a-verified-teacher-CS-Principles-and-CS-Discoveries-only-) to become a verified teacher."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4f9218ff-1d7c-4408-a619-e5f4085590ab",
        "lesson_activity.key": "911a527c-f6c9-45c4-8483-033415340b87"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7374070a-7e02-44bf-9956-fd6d6bbea6bf",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Overview:** Have students read through the directions on the first page of the activity guide. The first part of this activity asks students to match different users to an song that suits their needs. Students will need to visit Code Studio to view the song prototypes.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "**Example Song Player:** This lesson is an opportunity for students to familiarize themselves with the \"Example Player\" embedded into levels. In these levels, this is the only way students can interact with each level. In future lessons, these examples provide guidance to students on how to complete their songs, so it's important students are familiar with this player!"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7374070a-7e02-44bf-9956-fd6d6bbea6bf",
        "lesson_activity.key": "911a527c-f6c9-45c4-8483-033415340b87"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b1fb1cab-a167-4669-b805-4f2f4eae1183",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Client Stories"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b1fb1cab-a167-4669-b805-4f2f4eae1183",
        "lesson_activity.key": "911a527c-f6c9-45c4-8483-033415340b87"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6344412a-f002-446f-bf44-f3cb670e23f1",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Circulate:** Have students work through this activity in pairs, encouraging discussion about why exactly they are choosing each template. This is a great place to discuss different songdesigns and the needs of each client.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "**Value Reasoning over Correctness:** There are more than one answer for some of the clients. Students are encouraged to use their own reasoning and logic when recommending a prototype to their client. It's okay for students to not make an \"obvious\" choice as long as they're thinking carefully about their reasoning and are able to justify their choices."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6344412a-f002-446f-bf44-f3cb670e23f1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "911a527c-f6c9-45c4-8483-033415340b87"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6fb10a85-3e74-4cc2-8a3a-3eb358d998b0",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Share Out:** Have students discuss the following questions in small groups before bringing them to a full class discussion:\n* Which users were the easiest to find matches for?\n* Which users were the hardest to find matches for?\n\nBased on your observations while circulating, you should also identify a few specific users to ask the class to discuss, especially users for whom multiple students chose different templates for that user. Encourage students to hear different justifications for their choices, emphasizing that the rationale is more important than the choice itself.\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "As students discuss their reasoning for their choices, check to ensure that they are identifying the particular client's needs and characteristics, rather than general reasons to prefer a song. You may want to challenge students to distinguish their own needs and preferences from those of the described client."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6fb10a85-3e74-4cc2-8a3a-3eb358d998b0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "911a527c-f6c9-45c4-8483-033415340b87"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d4a2613d-94f3-4e7e-b282-11c671e7839b",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Now we've been asked to design a song ourselves for a client. We can create our own design, but it should meet the needs of our users.",
        "name": "Designing a Song",
        "progression_name": "Prepare & Try",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "**Note on Timing:** Depending on how long the warm-up took, especially if the class watched the problem-solving video, you may run out of time to fully complete this activity. That's okay! It can be something students come back to as they progress throughout the unit, or you may decide to extend this activity into a new class period and stretch out the design and feedback process. This task can be implemented in a variety of ways to match the constraints of the classroom."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d4a2613d-94f3-4e7e-b282-11c671e7839b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "911a527c-f6c9-45c4-8483-033415340b87"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "78301407-3054-4296-ac9d-c67ca916ee6c",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Overview:** Have students flip to the back of their activity guide and read the overview of the next part of the activity. Students will choose a user to create a song design for, following the Problem-Solving Process. \n\n**Transition** Have students navigate to Lesson 1, Level 2. During the \"Prepare & Try\" section of their Activity Guide, they are asked to explore different sounds in the Code.org Sound Library. When they find a sound that meets their client's needs, they should write down the sound name on their Activity Guide. \n\n**Circulate:** Monitor students as they complete this activity, ensuring that students are creating designs that match the needs of the user they chose. Monitor student conversations as well to make sure both voices are being heard during discussions and decisions. Students will be working in pairs throughout the unit, so it can be good to intervene early to reinforce good collaboration habits.\n\n**(Optional) Share Out:** Depending on how much time is left in class, allow students to trade with other groups and share their song ideas. Encourage students to share with another group who picked the same user so they can see similarities and differences in their designs.\n\n",
        "progression_name": "Prepare & Try",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "**Exploring Different Sounds:** Music Lab provides a wide variety of custom sounds that students can integrate into songs. This level provides an explicit opportunity for students to explore this wide library of sounds in an open-ended way. Ideally, students \"get it all out of their system\" in this level and can then focus on solving problems in future lessons. So - really lean-in to letting students explore and identify sounds they like so it doesn't become a distraction in future lessons and projects!"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "78301407-3054-4296-ac9d-c67ca916ee6c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "911a527c-f6c9-45c4-8483-033415340b87"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "220ea34d-be99-4278-9dc3-fdcb07f870ca",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "**Following the Problem-Solving Process:** You can use student responses on the activity guide to determine how well they followed each step of the problem-solving process. This process will be reinforced throughout the unit, especially on projects."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "220ea34d-be99-4278-9dc3-fdcb07f870ca",
        "lesson_activity.key": "911a527c-f6c9-45c4-8483-033415340b87"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fe928a52-2b84-45cb-8f36-7e9625c00baa",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Prompt:** Reflect - What was one thing that you think your design does well to meet the needs of the user? What’s an area that you think can still be improved to meet the needs of your user?\n\n**Circulate:** Students can answer these prompts on their activity guide in the Reflect section of the Problem Solving Process.\n\n**Share Out:** Have students share their responses, highlighting similarities between responses even when the users were different.\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fe928a52-2b84-45cb-8f36-7e9625c00baa",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c9cd0acf-2725-4f6d-970b-c9c61216e759"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "18c98b22-3882-4ca9-bc84-f2d4595c72c7",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Have students complete the survey on the last level of the lesson. ",
        "name": "Reflection",
        "progression_name": "Student Survey"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "18c98b22-3882-4ca9-bc84-f2d4595c72c7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c9cd0acf-2725-4f6d-970b-c9c61216e759"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5ae8c28d-45ae-40f7-891e-e1d9fe3b5c6e",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "The next set of lessons introduces **Sequencing** with brand new blocks and programming strategies. Feel prepared to teach these lessons by reviewing our Self-Paced Professional Learning specifically for these lessons - in under 30 minutes! [**Click here to start now!**](https://studio.code.org/s/self-paced-pl-teaching-computer-science-discoveries-music-lab/lessons/2/levels/1)",
        "name": "Just-In-Time Professional Learning"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5ae8c28d-45ae-40f7-891e-e1d9fe3b5c6e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9de60e29-602a-40f1-9e14-9f2b777a3724"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4d221d3b-3fd2-4e6b-beb9-f9edb31f780d",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "- **This is a pilot, so things change!** Please always refer to the Slide Decks and Speaker Notes for the latest updates.\n- If the rest of this lesson plan is blank, don't worry! It just means we're still in the process of updating this lesson plan on our website and that process can sometimes get delayed! However, **the slides are always up to date** and the speaker notes contain everything you need to run the lesson. "
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4d221d3b-3fd2-4e6b-beb9-f9edb31f780d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "768f4781-a97c-4a82-b41b-19106e8c6eac"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f8457824-762e-409e-8881-5a80ac2b1c31",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-video-camera\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Video:**  Show the [Make Music, Learn Code](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GqlP5s7KTl4) video\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** What's one example from the video of how music pairs with technology?\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Use this prompt to surface observations from the video about how music and technology are interconnected, such as designing songs fully \"within the box\". Extend the discussion to highlight areas that students may be excited by as they learn more about music lab.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show students the four aspects of computational thinking:\n- **Algorithmic Thinking:** Going step-by-step to solve a problem\n- **Pattern Recognition:** Using similarities and patterns to solve a problem\n- **Abstraction:** Breaking down a problem into smaller pieces\n- **Decomposition:** Focusing on important details to solve a problem\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-microphone\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Say:</strong> There are many ways music and technology are connected in real-life, but another important aspect is how musicians and computer scientists think about creating songs or solving problems. Throughout this unit, we're going to explore four key computational mindsets for how to create songs with code. Be on the lookout for these as we learn more about Music Lab today!",
        "progression_name": "Make Music, Learn Code Video"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f8457824-762e-409e-8881-5a80ac2b1c31",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ad57c037-c71a-4e78-849f-e58668ea0226"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9ac1d7a0-0474-43cb-b2cd-791a27c69828",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students open the Explore level and read the instructions. Students are asked to complete a series of tasks to help them become familiar with navigating Music Lab. Give students time to explore and experiment on their own.",
        "progression_name": "Explore",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "**Play Together - an Impossible Task:** This level purposefully challenges students to do something that is not possible with the set of blocks they have: play 3 sounds simultaneously. This is the last challenge on the list and the only one that is not possible to do. While this may initially confuse students, it can be used as motivation for the next level which introduces the Play Together block. Once you notice students are starting to work on this challenge, regroup the class to explain this level and then continue to the next one where this block is introduced."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9ac1d7a0-0474-43cb-b2cd-791a27c69828",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4d02d064-ba85-4a87-9f55-bf04c81897b7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "16a0bcc9-e30f-492c-9bfc-114d480ad7db",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Regroup:** As a class, go through each of the tasks in the level. Ask students to explain how they solved certain tasks before explaining yourself. Be sure to highlight that students can click on the <i class=\"fa-solid fa-lightbulb\"></i> <i class=\"fa-solid fa-square-right\"></i> icons to see special callouts as hints within the level.\n\n[Click here to see a video of a curriculum team member exploring this level](https://www.loom.com/share/01b5fd8ef8f04002b09f61fbfdf6dc9a), highlighting each of the tasks in this level and additional features in music lab. You can decide how many of these features you would like to show to the whole class."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "16a0bcc9-e30f-492c-9bfc-114d480ad7db",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4d02d064-ba85-4a87-9f55-bf04c81897b7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "642100fe-ebac-480f-b62a-85eddbc3cae5",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students continue to the Predict level. Have students respond to the two questions within the level:\n- Write down anything you **notice** about the code\n- Make a **prediction** - what do you think will happen when you press Run?\n\nOnce students have made a prediction, they can press Run to see the result.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "**No Wrong Answers** - These questions are intentionally structured to encourage \"no wrong answer\" thinking, which invites students to make unstructured observations and participate in class discussions. These predict levels are based on the PRIMM pedagogy for teaching coding, which shows increased engagement and ownership when students are asked to form hypotheses about code before seeing it in action. As you structure these discussions, ensure all students feel supported in participating and try to avoid confirming or denying any ideas and instead letting students make those observations themselves when running the code."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "642100fe-ebac-480f-b62a-85eddbc3cae5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4d02d064-ba85-4a87-9f55-bf04c81897b7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6d64c6d6-eb3e-47e2-89ca-415643ca9a42",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Predict"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6d64c6d6-eb3e-47e2-89ca-415643ca9a42",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4d02d064-ba85-4a87-9f55-bf04c81897b7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3943702d-64cc-43f4-bd52-bc8949dbf36b",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Once the class has seen the code, lead a discussion about what went as expected and what was surprising. Explicitly explain how the `play together` block works, and that since the Bass track is on the outside it will play afterwards. Ensure students understand why the code behaves the way it does before continuing. "
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3943702d-64cc-43f4-bd52-bc8949dbf36b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4d02d064-ba85-4a87-9f55-bf04c81897b7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0aa3cbdd-b64f-4418-9cda-24858cc8fd21",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Decide how you would like students to continue through the investigate levels. Here are some options:\n\n- **Complete as a Class:** Guide students through completing these levels, modeling how to interact with the workspace and the new code blocks. The class can feel like a communal Pair Programming experience, with you acting as the driver and the class acting as the navigator providing suggestions and steps for how to solve each level. Once the Investigate levels are completed as a class, students can skip to the Check-In to complete independently\n- **Independent First, Check as a Class**: Set a timer and allow students to start the levels independently or with partners. Once the timer is up, go over the levels as a class. Students can choose whether or not to pause and listen, or quietly continue in the lessons. This allows students who have been to quietly continue through the levels, while students who may be struggling are able to follow along as a class and compare their work to the correct answers\n- **Independently with Support:** Students work through the Investigate levels with structured supports for if they get stuck, such as providing red, yellow, and green \"stop signs\" for students to self-reflect on how they're feeling about the lesson so far and invite intervention if needed.",
        "progression_name": "Investigate",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "**Viewing Example Solutions:** Each level has an example solution that verified teachers can access and view. You can view example solutions by expanding the Teacher Panel from the right-side of the screen, then clicking the blue \"Example Solution\" button. This process is [highlighted in this video](https://www.loom.com/share/36ee8c6709aa4e8dbe2449103e1b07be) and the graphic below\n\n<img src=\"https://images.code.org/e2be70507c3a22a08d28a3cd7c8cdd5a-example-solutions.png\" style=\"width: 25%\">"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0aa3cbdd-b64f-4418-9cda-24858cc8fd21",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4d02d064-ba85-4a87-9f55-bf04c81897b7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "24ab1767-e0bc-4d27-ba75-f759d1cd7e9b",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Check-in on students as they complete these levels. If students get stuck, encourage them to:\n- Read the step-by-step instructions\n- Click the <i class=\"fa-solid fa-lightbulb\"></i> <i class=\"fa-solid fa-square-right\"></i> icons for hints\n- Listen to the example song for clues\n- Talk through their process with a neighbor\n\nAlso notice students who have found success or unique ways to solve a level in case you want to call on them later to explain their thinking.\n\nOnce enough students have completed the Investigate levels, consider regrouping to talk through the levels as a class. This is a good opportunity to cement student thinking on key concepts from the lesson while also elevating student voices by calling on students to help you complete levels in front of the class."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "24ab1767-e0bc-4d27-ba75-f759d1cd7e9b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4d02d064-ba85-4a87-9f55-bf04c81897b7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b0dc769d-72d9-40fe-9ee6-f09a25d13716",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students continue to the Check-In level. The remaining levels can be completed independently at students' own pace."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b0dc769d-72d9-40fe-9ee6-f09a25d13716",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4d02d064-ba85-4a87-9f55-bf04c81897b7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4df44988-eae4-4a43-b5f7-386007c1e30f",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Check-In",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "**Formative Assessment:** Check-in levels are strategically placed in the middle of the lesson so you can check-in on how students are doing while they are still in the room with you and you can adjust instruction if needed. For example:\n- If you notice most students are able to complete the check-in with no assistance, the class can continue to the remaining problems\n- If most of the class is struggling with the check-in, consider regrouping as a class and completing the Investigate levels together or completing the check-in as a class\n- If a few students are struggling, consider working individually with those students to ensure they can be successful in later levels."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4df44988-eae4-4a43-b5f7-386007c1e30f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4d02d064-ba85-4a87-9f55-bf04c81897b7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "078cb9c3-a468-44f1-966f-000dabb30989",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students complete at least 2 practice levels. Practice levels are designed to be around the same level of difficulty, but may ask students to apply skills in different ways."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "078cb9c3-a468-44f1-966f-000dabb30989",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4d02d064-ba85-4a87-9f55-bf04c81897b7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d1b30d96-c9b6-408d-bdde-d1b070138502",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Practice",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "**Facilitating Practice Levels:** Practice levels are designed for students to apply their knowledge from the previous levels and develop fluency in using the new blocks of code to solve problems. Students can choose which practice levels they would like to complete, and it’s not necessary for a student to complete each practice level before continuing.\n\nStudents tend to be more engaged and respond better when they have an authentic choice about how to continue their learning. Allow students to choose practice levels according to their interests and level of comfort, and consider providing opportunities for students to demonstrate and explain their solutions to the practice levels they chose to the entire class.\n\n**Computational Thinking:** Practice levels intentionally incorporate computational thinking practices - as students complete levels, you can ask about the particular computational thinking practice they used in the level (for example: algorithmic thinking or debugging). This will also help prime students for the wrap-up reflection on computational thinking practices."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d1b30d96-c9b6-408d-bdde-d1b070138502",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4d02d064-ba85-4a87-9f55-bf04c81897b7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "54f501c4-7ec4-48be-8ac4-dd595d846c3a",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students complete the assessment independently",
        "progression_name": "Assessment",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "**Evaluative Assessment:** Assessment levels are provided towards the end of a lesson as a culmination of the skills being emphasized in the lesson. If you need to check only one level in this whole lesson, it can be this level. They are designed to be checked after class, allowing you to decide if you want to adjust instruction for the next day's lesson. For example:\n- If most students struggle with the assessment level, it may be worth starting tomorrow's class with a quick review and completing one of the practice levels they skipped in today's lesson.\n- If most students are successful in the assessment level, you can continue with the planned warm-up or you can encourage students to complete one of the challenge levels they may have skipped."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "54f501c4-7ec4-48be-8ac4-dd595d846c3a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4d02d064-ba85-4a87-9f55-bf04c81897b7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ce2f9704-c436-4605-9a73-98837e5777b3",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **(Optional) Do This:** Have students complete as many Challenge levels as they can.",
        "progression_name": "Challenge",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "**Facilitating Challenge Levels:** Challenge levels are designed as extensions to the concepts and skills students learn throughout a lesson. Challenge levels tend to focus on more open-ended tasks for students to complete, or opportunities to combine several skills from previous lessons together into one program.\n\nChallenge levels do **not** need to be completed for students to meet the core objectives of a lesson. Instead, every task in a challenge level is meant to supplement and enrich the learning objectives of a lesson, but are not required for future lessons. Students can still demonstrate mastery of the objectives of a lesson without completing any of the challenge levels."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ce2f9704-c436-4605-9a73-98837e5777b3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4d02d064-ba85-4a87-9f55-bf04c81897b7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5e685e17-9421-4f73-ad4e-824d11bba621",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** What's an example of how you used computational thinking in one of the levels today?\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should refer back to the Practice levels they completed and the strategies highlighted in each level. By sharing out, students get to hear about choice levels they may have skipped and get new ideas for how computational thinking is tied to building songs with code. Consider having students complete this discussion using the speed pair protocol or another strategy where students can hear many different perspectives quickly"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5e685e17-9421-4f73-ad4e-824d11bba621",
        "lesson_activity.key": "409a1d0e-1abd-4621-b114-29cc0ee9d5ad"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c506ec96-16e4-4f05-809c-9aa5bd805dbb",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Have students complete the survey on the last level of the lesson. ",
        "progression_name": "Student Survey"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c506ec96-16e4-4f05-809c-9aa5bd805dbb",
        "lesson_activity.key": "409a1d0e-1abd-4621-b114-29cc0ee9d5ad"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3f17936c-3d36-4f9a-bed0-fe5c6ded1ab8",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "After class has ended, use the Teacher Dashboard to review how much progress students made and how well they did on the Assessment level. Some things to notice might be:\n- Did most students make it to the Assessment level, or are there still a lot of empty progress bubbles?\n- Did students make it to the Assessment level, but did not complete it (ie: green outlines with white circles)?\n- Did students finish the Assessment level and continue to the challenge levels?\n\nBased on these observations, you can adapt the warm up tomorrow to best meet the needs of the class.",
        "name": "Reviewing the Assessment Level"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3f17936c-3d36-4f9a-bed0-fe5c6ded1ab8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "002a446b-7149-4d74-8ea2-99488f88f9ae"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9ef35fb2-647a-4384-b6de-f180c164a136",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "- **This is a pilot, so things change!** Please always refer to the Slide Decks and Speaker Notes for the latest updates.\n- If the rest of this lesson plan is blank, don't worry! It just means we're still in the process of updating this lesson plan on our website and that process can sometimes get delayed! However, **the slides are always up to date** and the speaker notes contain everything you need to run the lesson. ",
        "name": "Pilot Information"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9ef35fb2-647a-4384-b6de-f180c164a136",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b41dd4a5-af0e-488d-960f-f021011aef01"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "24139e37-0313-4c4c-b395-410faabcdaf2",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Before teaching today's lesson, be sure to use the Teacher Dashboard to assess how students did to make a decision for how to start today's lesson. The Warm-Up for this lesson is adaptable based on how well students did with the Assessment level from the previous lesson. ",
        "name": "Reviewing the Assessment"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "24139e37-0313-4c4c-b395-410faabcdaf2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b41dd4a5-af0e-488d-960f-f021011aef01"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "042f14a8-82b4-4a9c-a38d-779a87a3c9a9",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Decide on how you want to start class based on your analysis of the Assessment level from the previous day:\n- If many students did not reach the Assessment or do well on it: **Whole-Class Reteach** -  go over one of the Practice levels as a class, then have students complete an Assessment or Challenge level\n- If some students did not reach the Assessment or do well: **Targeted Intervention** - have the class complete a challenge level from yesterday while you do targeted interventions with students who may have struggled\n- If most students completed the assessment and did well: **Start the lesson** - you can jump straight into today's lesson to give students more time to practice and reach the challenge levels.",
        "name": "Differentiated Warm-Up"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "042f14a8-82b4-4a9c-a38d-779a87a3c9a9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "80724a82-9e02-4980-944a-325920f361b6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "57857a4e-0ee5-475b-95c6-d1a4835b8996",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students get into pairs for Pair Programming, where one student is the driver and the other is the navigator. This process is highlighted in [this video](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q7d_JtyCq1A), which you can show to the class. You can have students switch roles based on a timer, or switch every time they complete a level. Students can pair program through the Practice levels, and then split back up for the Assessment level. ",
        "name": "Pair Programming",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "**Digging Deeper**: To learn more about pair programming in the classroom, check out the [K-12 Pair Programming Toolkit](https://www.etr.org/default/assets/File/projects/Pair%20Programming%20Toolkit_FINAL%207_30_19.pdf) from ETR. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "57857a4e-0ee5-475b-95c6-d1a4835b8996",
        "lesson_activity.key": "80724a82-9e02-4980-944a-325920f361b6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a2299a48-5771-4569-a050-cdda120648bb",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students work through the levels in class. Students can use their pair programming partners for support, along with the callout icons in instructions and the example music players.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Monitor students as they complete levels. Most of class is spent within levels, providing lots of opportunity to check-in individually with students as needed.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "**Prompts to Build Algorithmic Thinking:** Algorithmic Thinking is all about developing a step-by-step solution to the problem, or the rules to follow to solve the problem. In Music Lab, algorithmic thinking shows up when students follow steps to create a song, such as \"first I'll get my backing beats, then I'll layer in my leads, and finally I'll add the vocals\". Use these questions to help students identify what’s essential in their song or code:\n\n* What steps did you follow to build your song? Could you explain them in order?\n* If you had to teach someone else to build a similar track, what instructions would you give them?\n* Could you create a checklist to build a track like this again?\n\nThese tips come from our Self-Paced Professional Learning module - [click here to see additional tips and learn more about Algorithmic Thinking](https://studio.code.org/s/self-paced-pl-teaching-computer-science-discoveries-music-lab/lessons/2/levels/7)"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a2299a48-5771-4569-a050-cdda120648bb",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5501d6c6-fb4d-4225-a3b3-6355732cc7bf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6ca87f6d-c8b4-41d4-b343-417a60824d98",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Predict",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "**Viewing Example Solutions:** Each level has an example solution that verified teachers can access and view. You can view example solutions by expanding the Teacher Panel from the right-side of the screen, then clicking the blue \"Example Solution\" button. This process is [highlighted in this video](https://www.loom.com/share/36ee8c6709aa4e8dbe2449103e1b07be) and the graphic below\n\n<img src=\"https://images.code.org/e2be70507c3a22a08d28a3cd7c8cdd5a-example-solutions.png\" style=\"width: 25%\">"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6ca87f6d-c8b4-41d4-b343-417a60824d98",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5501d6c6-fb4d-4225-a3b3-6355732cc7bf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8837fee8-d533-4832-a431-2dc10369135a",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Play Sequential"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8837fee8-d533-4832-a431-2dc10369135a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5501d6c6-fb4d-4225-a3b3-6355732cc7bf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a3bd4a21-f724-4b81-8e2d-4b18ffa88825",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Check-in",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "**Formative Assessment:** Check-in levels are strategically placed in the middle of the lesson so you can check-in on how students are doing while they are still in the room with you and you can adjust instruction if needed. For example:\n- If you notice most students are able to complete the check-in with no assistance, the class can continue to the remaining problems\n- If most of the class is struggling with the check-in, consider regrouping as a class and completing the Investigate levels together or completing the check-in as a class\n- If a few students are struggling, consider working individually with those students to ensure they can be successful in later levels."
          }
        ]
      },
